**Explanation:**

*   **`@RestController`**:  This annotation marks the class as a REST controller, handling incoming web requests.
*   **`ChatClient chatClient;`**: This declares a field to hold an instance of the `ChatClient`.  Spring AI provides autoconfiguration to create a `ChatClient.Builder` bean.
*   **`MyController(ChatClient.Builder chatClientBuilder)`**: This is the constructor. It receives a `ChatClient.Builder` as a dependency (injected by Spring) and uses it to build the `ChatClient` instance.
*   **`@GetMapping("/ai")`**: This annotation maps the `/ai` endpoint to the `generation` method, handling GET requests.
*   **`String generation(String userInput)`**: This method takes the user's input as a `String`.
*   **`this.chatClient.prompt().user(userInput).call().content();`**: This is the core of the RAG interaction:
    *   `this.chatClient.prompt()`: Starts a new prompt.
    *   `.user(userInput)`: Sets the user's input as the message for the AI model.
    *   `.call()`: Sends the prompt to the AI model and retrieves the response.
    *   `.content()`: Extracts the text content of the AI model's response as a `String`, which is then returned by the method.

This example demonstrates the simplest use case where Spring AI's autoconfiguration creates a `ChatClient.Builder` bean that you can inject and use to interact with an AI model.  The user input is directly sent to the AI model, and the response is returned.  

For a more comprehensive RAG example with MongoDB, refer to the detailed tutorial: [https://www.mongodb.com/developer/languages/java/retrieval-augmented-generation-spring-ai/](https://www.mongodb.com/developer/languages/java/retrieval-augmented-generation-spring-ai/)

